    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-30T10:50:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-29T01:36:00-05:00" n="1017"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1017">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/269.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Mexican Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexican Embassy</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <lb/> ([<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1912-03-30T10:50:00-05:00"
                            notBefore="1912-03-29T00:00:00-06:36">undated</date>;] Received March
                        30, 1912—10.50 a.m.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Consul of Mexico at New York tells me that a cargo of arms and ammunition has
                    gone out on the steamship <hi rend="italic">Monterey</hi> of the Ward Line,
                    bound for Mexico, and that the shipper assured him that he was duly authorized
                    by the Government of which your excellency <pb facs="0885" n="769"
                        xml:id="pg_769"/> forms part, notwithstanding that proper steps were not
                    taken in the manner referred to in your excellency’s note dated the 26th
                    instant, which was received to-day at 1 p.m., and to which an answer is now
                    being duly prepared with the appropriate expressions of thanks. In virtue
                    thereof, and owing to the urgency of the case, I permit myself to trespass upon
                    your excellency’s attention in order that you may be pleased to tell me whether
                    the aforesaid consul’s asseveration is accurate.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Crespo.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
